{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565552"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:28:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:28:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17530"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17530"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.08,0.01,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10220"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56632"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3803"},{"type":"tags","id":"11184"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of fatigue, dizziness, and generalised weakness. She reports nausea, salt cravings, and has lost 4 kg in weight. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 85/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has areas of hyperpigmentation in her palmar creases and buccal mucosa. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following electrolyte abnormalities is most consistent with this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperkalaemia with hyponatraemia","Hypokalaemia with hypernatraemia","Hyperkalaemia with hypernatraemia","Hypokalaemia with hyponatraemia","Normal potassium with hyponatraemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison\u0027s disease), including postural hypotension, hyperpigmentation, salt craving, and characteristic biochemical abnormalities. The key electrolyte disturbances in primary adrenal insufficiency are hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia with hyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic pattern seen in primary adrenal insufficiency. This occurs due to aldosterone deficiency, which normally promotes sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the distal tubule. Without aldosterone, sodium is lost in the urine leading to hyponatraemia, while potassium retention occurs leading to hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia with hypernatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E would not be consistent with adrenal insufficiency as the loss of aldosterone always leads to sodium wasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia with hypernatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E is more consistent with mineralocorticoid excess states such as primary hyperaldosteronism, where there is increased sodium retention and potassium excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia with hyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E might be seen in conditions such as diuretic use or gastrointestinal losses, but does not fit with the pathophysiology of adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal potassium with hyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in multiple conditions such as SIADH but would not be expected in adrenal insufficiency where potassium handling is invariably affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther biochemical features of adrenal insufficiency include hypoglycaemia (due to cortisol deficiency affecting gluconeogenesis) and a mild metabolic acidosis (due to aldosterone deficiency). The combination of hyperkalaemia and hyponatraemia should always prompt consideration of adrenal insufficiency, particularly in a patient with compatible clinical features.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary adrenal insufficiency typically presents with hyperkalaemia and hyponatraemia."],"references":["Ghada Elshimy, Venu Chippa, Kaur J, Jeong JM. Adrenal Crisis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK499968/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56632"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17530"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56632"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T15:36:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T15:37:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10220"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71161"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a